<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-009-128 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 509 558</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 21 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New vision system for robots introduced. (Georgia Institute ofTechnology's Gereric Retroreflective Integrated Parts Pick-UpSystem)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     New TechniqueRobot ArmsColleges and UniversitiesRobotsGeorgia Institute of Technology.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>New Vision System For Robots Introduced 11/21/91 ATLANTA, GEORGIA, U.S.A.,andO;1991 NOV 21 (NB) -- The Georgia Institute of Technology, better known asGeorgia Tech, announced a new vision system for robots called the GerericRetroreflective Integrated Parts Pick-Up System, or GRIPPS.andM;GRIPPS uses a digital camera mounted on the arm of a parts retrieval robot,and loads the outline of each part to be picked up into the robot's memory.andM;Parts are then put in a simple, low-cost tray coated with retroreflectivepaint and placed near the robot, explained Dr. Kok-Meng Lee, project directorof the school's Material Handling Research Center.andP;  The reflective paintgives the camera a high- contrast, two-dimensional image of the parts, whichare then matched to memory.andM;The big advantage of GRIPPS is its cost, Lee said -- which is underandM;$5,000.andP;  The new system is also fast.andP;  A robot equipped with it can pick up anumber of items in one second, while other systems require 4-10 seconds toretrieve a single part.andM;Patents are being applied for on the system.andP;  The research was sponsored byGeneral Motors, Ford and the National Science Foundation.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19911121/Press Contact: John Toon, Georgia Tech, 894-3444)</TEXT></DOC>